{{Further|List of United Nations peacekeeping missions}} Canada's role in the development of [[peacekeeping]] during the 20th century led to the establishment of [[Canada]] as a prominent world power. Canada's commitment to multilateralism has been closely related to [[History of United Nations peacekeeping|peacekeeping efforts]]. Canadian [[Nobel Peace Prize]] laureate [[Lester B. Pearson]] is considered to be the father of modern [[United Nations]] Peacekeeping.<ref name="Sharma2008">{{cite book|author=Banerjee & Sharma|title=Reinventing the United Nations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j-xHSiPhueEC&pg=PA63|date=1 March 2008|publisher=PHI Learning Pvt. Ltd.|isbn=978-81-203-3282-9|page=63}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Cohen|first=Andrew|title=Lester B. Pearson|year=2008|publisher=Penguin Canada|location=Toronto|pages=114–116}}</ref> Prior to Canada's role in the [[Suez Canal Crisis]], Canada was viewed by many as insignificant in issues of the world's traditional powers. Canada's successful role in the conflict gave Canada credibility and established it as a nation fighting for the common good of all the world's nations and not just their allies.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gaffen|first=Fred|title=In The Eye of The Storm: A History of Canadian Peacekeeping|year=1987|publisher=Deneau & Wayne Publishers LTD.|location=Toronto|page=43}}</ref> Since 1995, however, Canadian direct participation in United Nations peacekeeping efforts has greatly declined.<ref name="JohnsonJoshee2007">{{cite book|author1=Lauri Johnson|author2=Reva Joshee|title=Multicultural education policies in Canada and the United States|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I8jr_pE3YPwC&pg=PA23|year=2007|publisher=UBC Press|isbn=978-0-7748-1325-9|page=23}}</ref> That number decreased largely because Canada began to direct its participation to UN-sanctioned military operations through [[NATO]], rather than through the UN.<ref name="McQuaig2010bt">{{cite book|author=Linda McQuaig|title=Holding the Bully's Coat: Canada and the U.S. Empire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9g4Xd12rIGYC&pg=PT50|date=4 June 2010|publisher=Random House Digital, Inc.|isbn=978-0-385-67297-9|page=50}}</ref> In July 2006, for instance, Canada ranked 51st on the list of UN peacekeepers, contributing 130 peacekeepers out of a total UN deployment of over 70,000;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/Depts/dpko/dpko/contributors/2006/july06_2.pdf|publisher=United Nations |title=Ranking of Military and Police Contributions to UN Operations |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2011-02-24}}</ref> whereas in November 1990 Canada had 1,002 troops out of a total UN deployment of 10,304.<ref>{{cite web|title=Troop and police contributors archive (1990–2011) |url=https://www.un.org/en/peacekeeping/resources/statistics/contributors_archive.shtml|date=2010|publisher=United Nations|accessdate=2012-01-01}}</ref>
*Below is a list of major peacekeeping missions undertaken by Canada from 1956 to present.<ref>{{cite web|title=Peacekeeping|url=http://www.canadiansoldiers.com/history/peacekeeping/peacekeeping.htm|publisher=canadiansoldiers|year=2008|accessdate=2010-04-16}}</ref>
