=== Series 2 (2017) === The BBC announced that the programme had been recommissioned for a second series on 5 March 2016. In a press release, Ullman stated: "It has been a pleasure being back at the BBC, and I am thrilled to get the opportunity to write more shows with my brilliant team. The warm reception from the British public has meant a lot to me personally. I want to thank them and let Dame Judi Dench and Chancellor Angela Merkel know I couldn’t have done it without you girls. Here's to season two."<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=BBC One's Tracey Ullman's Show to return for second series – Media Centre |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2016/tracey-ullman-second-series |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=5 March 2016 |access-date=5 March 2016}}</ref>
Filming on series 2 began on 27 June 2016 and wrapped on 19 August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allabouttracey.com/2016/07/tracey-ullmans-show-series-2-starts.html|title=Tracey Ullman's Show Series 2 Starts Production!|publisher=Allabouttracey.com|date=3 July 2016|accessdate=7 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=screenings2>{{cite web|url=http://www.allabouttracey.com/2016/08/screenings-for-series-2-of-tracey.html|title=SCREENINGS FOR SERIES 2 OF TRACEY ULLMAN'S SHOW SCHEDULED FOR SEPTEMBER!|publisher=Allabouttracey.com|date=31 August 2016|accessdate=7 October 2016}}</ref> On 2 July, BBC Comedy released a clip of Ullman made up as Angela Merkel reacting to the news that [[Boris Johnson]] had chosen not to run for [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/bbccomedy/status/749168716361920512|title=WATCH! Angela Merkel bashes @BorisJohnson for quitting the #ToryLeadership – Tracey Ullman's Show returns in January|publisher=Twitter.com|date=2 July 2016|accessdate=7 October 2016}}</ref> Comedian [[Ben Miller]] was confirmed as a guest star for a sketch in which he will play media mogul [[Rupert Murdoch]] with Ullman portraying wife and former model [[Jerry Hall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/ben-miller-death-in-paradise_uk_579a051ae4b02508de486616|title=EXCLUSIVE: Ben Miller Reveals The Real Reason He Quit ‘Death In Paradise’|publisher=The Huffington Post|date=31 July 2016|accessdate=7 October 2016}}</ref> Audience screenings of the new sketches took place at BBC Radio Theatre on 10, 11 September and 31 October.<ref name=productiondata/>
According to the ''Radio Times'', Ullman is set to impersonate [[Scottish National Party|SNP]] leader [[Nicola Sturgeon]], 'who will played like a Bond villain, living in a Tartan Lair with a white Scottie dog on her lap,' as well as an "eerily accurate" Clare Balding.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2016-10-10/tracey-ullman-lines-up-new-impressions-of-nicola-sturgeon-and-clare-balding|title=Tracey Ullman lines up new impressions of Nicola Sturgeon and Clare Balding|publisher=RadioTimes.com|date=10 October 2016|accessdate=10 October 2016}}</ref> English impressionist Luke Kempner was revealed to be joining the series. Impersonations of tennis pro [[Andy Murray]] and actor [[Simon Pegg]] impersonated by Kempner are expected to appear in the show's second series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/showbiz-tv/hot-tv/535866/Bucks-Fizz-singer-Cheryl-Baker-Eurovision-contestants-entries-old|title=Bucks Fizz singer Cheryl Baker wants OAPs banned from representing UK at Eurovision|publisher=Daily Star|date=7 August 2016|accessdate=29 October 2016}}</ref>
[[Brexit]] plays a part in the show's storyline. "This series, we wrote some material for the Angela Merkel character, but then two days before shooting we had the Brexit vote, which sidelined a lot of that material. So we had to do some very quick rewriting and produced a song about how she feels all alone now."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thesun.co.uk/tvandshowbiz/2711339/tracey-ullman-dame-judi-denchs-daughter-watch-my-sketches/|title=A GOOD IMPRESSION Tracey Ullman: ‘Dame Judi Dench's daughter says they watch my sketches at home’|work=[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]|accessdate=7 February 2017}}</ref> "It made it better, more poignant", says Ullman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2016/10/tracey-ullman-show-hbo-bbc-judi-dench-maggie-smith-angela-merkel-1201741293/|title=Tracey Ullman Says Her New HBO Sketch Series is the Antidote to TV's Rash of Bleak Comedies|publisher=[[IndieWire]]|accessdate=7 February 2017}}</ref>
Unlike series 1, each episode of series 2 opens with a parody of a BBC show before the opening title sequence.
A sketch involving Christian discrimination was lauded by Christian commentators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christiantoday.com/article/watch.comedian.tracey.ullmans.hilarious.take.on.a.christians.job.interview/105355.htm/|title=WATCH: Comedian Tracey Ullman's Hilarious Take On A Christian's Job Interview|publisher=ChristianToday|accessdate=7 March 2017}}</ref> A sketch which turns the tables on [[victim blaming]] in sexual assault cases received international critical acclaim after it went viral on social media (even in China).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nytlive.nytimes.com/womenintheworld/2017/03/13/tracey-ullman-stars-in-hilarious-skit-showing-ridiculousness-of-sexism/|title=Tracey Ullman stars in hilarious skit showing ridiculousness of sexism|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=13 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/tracey-ullman-gives-men-a-taste-of-the-worlds-ugliest-double-standard_us_58c60992e4b054a0ea6b6b53|title=Tracey Ullman Calls Out Sexist Double Standard In Hilarious Skit|publisher=[[The Huffington Post]]|accessdate=13 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/writersroom/entries/7c118655-c423-4755-bc6a-bd979f2807a5|title=The long journey to overnight success – writing a 'viral' hit for Tracey Ullman's Show|publisher=BBC.co.uk|accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref> The sketch was viewed over 32 million times.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/offbeat/satirical-take-on-victim-blaming-is-viral-28-million-views-and-counting-1671771|title=Satirical Take On Victim Blaming Is Viral. 28 Million Views And Counting|publisher=[[NDTV]]|accessdate=21 March 2017}}</ref>
