==Prior to 20th century==
{{History of Benin}}

* 1830 - Contonou founded as a "slaving port."{{sfn|Bradt|2006}}
* 1878 - Cotonou "ceded to France."<ref name="Houngnikpo2013">{{cite book|author1=Mathurin C. Houngnikpo|author2=Samuel Decalo |edition=4th |title=Historical Dictionary of Benin|year=2013|publisher=[[Scarecrow Press]] |isbn=978-0-8108-7171-7 |location=US }}</ref>
* 1883 - French occupation.<ref name="Vine2004" />
* 1899 - Wharf built.{{sfn|Cornevin|1980}}

==20th century==

* 1904 - Cotonou becomes part of colonial [[French Dahomey]].
* 1908 - Deepwater harbor opens.{{sfn|Bradt|2006}}
* 1912 - Cotonou becomes a "commune mixte."{{sfn|Cornevin|1980}}
* 1920s - Population: 8,500.{{sfn|Cornevin|1980}}
* 1928 - [[Ancien Pont]] (bridge) built.
* 1955 - Catholic [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Cotonou|Metropolitan Archdiocese of Cotonou]] established.<ref name=katolsk>{{cite web |title=Chronology of Catholic Dioceses: Benin |url= http://www.katolsk.no/organisasjon/verden/chronology/benin |work=www.katolsk.no |publisher=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Oslo]] |location=Norway |accessdate=30 September 2014 }}</ref>
* 1957 - January: Pan-African [[General Union of Negro African Workers]] founded at a conference in Cotonou.
* 1960s - Tomety photo studio in operation.<ref name="PefferCameron2013">{{cite book|editor=John Peffer and Elisabeth L. Cameron|title=Portraiture and Photography in Africa|year= 2013|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=0-253-00872-7 |chapter=Yoruba Studio Photographers in Francophone West Africa |author=Erika Nimis |pages=102–140 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=hk4677rbgK4C }}</ref>
* 1963
** [[Dantokpa Market]] established.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}
** Presidential Palace built.<ref name="Houngnikpo2013" />
* 1964
** ''L'action populaire'' [[List of newspapers in Benin|newspaper]] begins publication.<ref name=CRLnewspapers>{{cite web |url=http://catalog.crl.edu/search~S35?/dCotonou+%28Benin%29+--+Newspapers |title= Cotonou (Benin) -- Newspapers |publisher=[[Center for Research Libraries]] |location=Chicago, US |work= Global Resources Network |accessdate=30 September 2014 }}</ref>
** Nigerian Yoruba Community-Cotonou organization formed.<ref name="Falola2009">{{cite book|editor=[[Toyin Falola]] and Aribidesi Adisa Usman|title=Movements, Borders, and Identities in Africa |year=2009|publisher=University Rochester Press|isbn=978-1-58046-296-9}}</ref>
* 1965 - Port constructed.<ref name="Houngnikpo2013" />
* 1967 - Les Muses theatre troupe formed.<ref name=rubin1997>{{cite book |editor=Don Rubin|title=World Encyclopedia of Contemporary Theatre |volume=3: Africa |year=1997|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-35949-1 |chapter=Benin |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SYmMAQAAQBAJ |page=57+ |display-editors=etal}}</ref>
* 1968 - [[Orchestre Poly Rythmo de Cotonou]] (musical group) and Société Béninoise de Textiles<ref name="Houngnikpo2013" /><ref name=europa2004-africa>{{cite book |title=Africa South of the Sahara 2004 |series=Regional Surveys of the World |publisher= [[Europa Publications]] |year=2004 |isbn= 1857431839 |chapter= Benin: Directory |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jj4J-AXGDaQC }}</ref> established in Cotonou.
* 1970 - [[National University of Benin|Université du Dahomey]] founded.
* 1975 - City becomes part of the [[People's Republic of Benin]].
* 1980 - Association des écrivains et critiques littéraires du Bénin founded.<ref name="Salhi2000">{{cite book|editor=Kamal Salhi|title=Francophone Studies: Discourse and Identity |year= 2000|publisher=Elm Bank |location=Exeter, UK |isbn=978-1-902454-05-4 |chapter=Discourse in the Periodicals of 20th-Century Benin }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://library.howard.edu/content.php?pid=555641&sid=4579735 |publisher=[[Howard University]] Library |title=African & Caribbean Literature in French |author= Mohamed Mekkawi |accessdate=30 September 2014 }}</ref>
* 1981 - Population: 383,250 (estimate).<ref>{{cite book |url= https://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/1980_round.htm |title=1985 Demographic Yearbook |year=1987 |author=[[United Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs]], Statistical Office |location=New York |chapter=Population of capital cities and cities of 100,000 and more inhabitants |pages=247-289 }}</ref>
* 1982 - [[Stade de l'Amitié]] (stadium) opens.
* 1988 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Musée olympique du Bénin|fr}} opens.
* 1986 - Sister city relationship established with Salvador, Brazil.<ref>{{citation |work=New York Times |date=5 August 1987 |title=Ouidah Journal; A Cultural Bond That Bondage Could Not Crush |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/08/05/world/ouidah-journal-a-cultural-bond-that-bondage-could-not-crush.html }}</ref>
* 1990 - February: Benin constitutional conference held.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jeuneafrique.com/Chronologie-pays_61_Bénin |language=French |title=Benin: Chronologie |work= [[Jeune Afrique]] |accessdate=30 September 2014 }}</ref>
* 1992 - Population: 536,827.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/1990_round.htm |title=1995 Demographic Yearbook |year=1997 |author=United Nations Department for Economic and Social Information and Policy Analysis, Statistics Division |location=New York |chapter=Population of capital cities and cities of 100,000 and more inhabitants |pages=262-321 }}</ref>
* 1995
** Centre de conferences international opens.{{sfn|Petit Futé|2011}}
** December: Meeting of the [[Organisation internationale de la Francophonie]] held in city.<ref name="Vine2004">{{cite book|author=Victor T. Le Vine|title=Politics in Francophone Africa|year=2004|publisher=Lynne Rienner Publishers|isbn=978-1-58826-249-3}}</ref>
* 1996 - [[University of Science and Technology of Benin]] established.

==21st century==
[[File:Lagune de Cotonou.jpg|thumb|right|Cotonou, 2013]]

* 2001 - ''L'Informateur'' [[List of newspapers in Benin|newspaper]] begins publication.<ref name=europa2004-africa /><ref>{{cite web |title=City Guide: Journaux |work=Cotonou ça bouge |url=http://cotonou-ca-bouge.net/-Journaux-.html |publisher=Portail Internet des Villes Africaines |language=French |accessdate=30 September 2014 }}</ref>
* 2002 - Maison des Médias du Bénin founded.<ref>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090426111327/http://www.mdmbenin.org/ |title=Maison des Médias |location=Cotonou |language=French |archivedate= 26 April 2009 |deadurl=yes |url=http://www.mdmbenin.org }}</ref><ref name=stanford>{{cite web |url= http://www-sul.stanford.edu/depts/ssrg/africa/benin/benin-newspapers-news.html |title=Benin: News |work=Africa South of the Sahara: Selected Internet Resources |publisher=Stanford University |location=US |editor=Karen Fung |accessdate=30 September 2014 }}</ref>
* 2003
** 25 December: [[UTAGE Flight 141|Airplane crash]].<ref name=bbc-timeline>{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-13040372 |title=Benin Profile: Timeline |work=BBC News |accessdate=30 September 2014 }}</ref>
** [[Nicéphore Soglo]] becomes mayor.
* 2005 - {{Interlanguage link multi|Fondation Zinsou|fr}} (museum) opens.{{sfn|Petit Futé|2011}}
* 2009 - Population: 815,041.<ref>{{cite book |title=Britannica Book of the Year 2014|year=2014|publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica|isbn=978-1-62513-171-3 |chapter=Benin |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=LccRAwAAQBAJ |page=549+ }}</ref>
* 2011 - Population: 924,000.<ref name=unhabitat2014>{{cite web |url=http://unhabitat.org/the-state-of-african-cities-2014/ |title=The State of African Cities 2014 |isbn=978-92-1-132598-0 |publisher=[[United Nations Human Settlements Programme]] |accessdate=30 September 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140910195641/https://unhabitat.org/the-state-of-african-cities-2014/ |archivedate=10 September 2014 |df= }}</ref>

